    <text id="B0026T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Jackson's letter to Joseph Milsted relates an accusation against Milsted's wife,
                    who beat the child of Peyton Harris, a man whom Milsted employs. Jackson also
                    states that Milsted has no right to beat anyone, and that he must supply
                    reasonable cause in order to breach a contract.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen, and Abandoned Lands<lb/>Office 4th Division, 9th
                    Sub-District, Virginia,
                    <name type="recipient">Mr. Joseph Milsted<lb/>Augusta <abbr expan="County"
                        >Co</abbr></name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-06-04">June 4th, 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Sir</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>Peyton Harris (<abbr expan="colored">C</abbr>) complains of bad treatment of his
                    child by your wife and that you attempt to break an agreement made with him for
                    present year.</p>

                <p>I need not tell you that the law gives you no right to beat or threaten to beat
                    anyone and before you can put Harris out of his house and garden you must assign
                    sufficent reason, such a breach of agreement on his part.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours</salute>
                    <signed>Tho<hi rend="super">s</hi> P. Jackson<lb/>Agent</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
